  "contentData": [
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/2bec0a09c0d04d968938115040312d94",
      "title": "Should I self-isolate if I have coronavirus, and for how long?",
      "content": "<p>While self-isolation is no longer a legal requirement, the University (and the Scottish Government) asks staff and students with COVID symptoms to stay at home. For guidance on this, see  <a href=\"https://www.nhsinform.scot/self-help-guides/self-help-guide-when-and-how-long-to-self-isolate-due-to-coronavirus\" title=\"NHS Inform\">NHS Inform</a>.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/10038dc1b7744576a2ba8f0334076af0",
      "title": "Do I need to tell in the University if I am self-isolating, suspect I have COVID, or have a positive COVID test?",
      "content": "<p>There is no longer a requirement to report to the University if you have COVID, or suspect you have.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/89f384d9153a44fead4e996ebe49926e",
      "title": "What if I am due to travel on University business?",
      "content": "<p>The University will consider requests for overseas travel on a case by case basis. If you are a staff member with plans to travel abroad on QMU business, you should first complete the standard international travel risk assessment with reference to the following websites:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice\" title=\"Government foreign travel advice\">Foreign travel advice from the government</a> </li>\n<li><a href=\"https://travelhealthpro.org.uk/\" title=\"Travel Health Pro\">Travel Health Pro</a> </li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.drum-cussac.net/self-registration\" title=\"drum cussac\">drum cussac</a> (all staff members can register with their QMU email address)</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Travel to countries with a <a href=\"https://www.drum-cussac.net/login?next=%2F\" title=\"Country risk rating\" data-anchor=\"?next=%2F\">Drum Cussac Overall Country Risk Rating</a> of 1-3 (Low to Moderate) can be approved by the HoD/appropriate manager if your overall risk assessment is also Low to Moderate.* Travel to Countries at Threat Levels 4 and 5 and/or overall risk assessments of High-Very High should always be referred to the  <a href=\"mailto:hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk\">QMU Health and Safety</a> team for guidance.  You should check any city destination(s) that you are visiting as well as the overall country risk rating, as assessed risk in a city may be different to the overall risk rating for the country.</p>\n<p>*Your assessment of the level of risk will partly depend on the nature of the activity you intend to undertake. For instance, conference attendance is relatively low risk compared with field based research activities.</p>\n<p>In planning your travel and discussing it with your line manager, you should also be mindful of what the University’s Travel Insurance will and won’t cover, particularly with regards to COVID related disruption (see below).</p>\n<p><strong>Travel Insurance Cover</strong></p>\n<p>The University’s UMAL <a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/finance/_layouts/15/WopiFrame.aspx\" title=\"Travel cover summary\">travel cover summary is available on the intranet</a>.  Briefly, the position is that there is no cover for any disruption arising out of COVID, such as needing to cancel or rearrange flights or the cost of additional accommodation if there is a requirement to isolate or if there is a travel ban, or if a conference is cancelled or rearranged. Other elements of the travel policy, such as personal injury or emergency medical expenses will still be covered – this will also cover emergency medical expenses where a member of staff develops COVID whilst overseas.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/f47b9581a42d4ec480788e0a26d9383c",
      "title": "Where can I find advice on personal travel?",
      "content": "<p>Please see the <a href=\"https://www.gov.scot/publications/coronavirus-covid-19-international-travel-quarantine/\">Scottish Government website</a>.</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/479028cde7e14c4fae000f18c4b6b89d",
      "title": "Where can I find guidance on remote working and video conferencing?",
      "content": "<p>See our <a href=\"/study-here/learning-facilities/it-services/you-can-do-it-at-home/\">you can do IT at home</a> webpage for information, guidance and tips.</p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/e4857737d94d472a8f584204589cb02d",
      "title": "What ventilation is there on campus?",
      "content": "<p>The campus buildings have modern ventilation systems that have been designed to meet building standards and the fresh air provision is through natural ventilation (i.e. windows), mechanical ventilation that provides 100% fresh air, or a combination of both. The mechanical ventilation is primarily supplied through floor grilles but can also be via high-level grilles. In line with Health and Safety Executive (HSE) recommendations, our ventilation systems are set to be fully operational from two hours before occupation and continue two hours post occupation to purge the buildings. The Estates team continue to monitor the performance of the system via the Building Management System and audit the air quality in spaces by deploying portable CO2 monitors, as appropriate.  </p>\n<p><a href=\"https://myshare.qmu.ac.uk/services/campus-commercial-services/covid19/_layouts/15/WopiFrame.aspx?sourcedoc={3F2FF3A1-F3B1-4A55-8372-830360F082BE}&amp;file=FAQs%20for%20Intranet%20V1.0%20(1).pdf&amp;action=default\" title=\"FAQ\" data-anchor=\"?sourcedoc={3F2FF3A1-F3B1-4A55-8372-830360F082BE}&amp;file=FAQs%20for%20Intranet%20V1.0%20(1).pdf&amp;action=default\">FAQ's related to ventilation (intranet link)</a></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/47e1f664aa8e4f1381a63783350bc875",
      "title": "Who do I contact if I have questions or concerns about the University's approach to COVID?",
      "content": "<p>Please speak to your line manager in the first instance. Beyond that, your Senior Leadership Team member is your route into the COVID Response Group, which is handling the University's COVID response.  For health and safety matters, please email hs-staff@qmu.ac.uk). </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/1a0b05db953849adb437560244d7b8bb",
      "title": "Can I get time off for a vaccination appointment?",
      "content": "<p>We encourage all staff to take the opportunity of COVID vaccination.  You are entitled to reasonable time off during your normal working hours to attend medical appointments, including an appointment to receive your vaccination. When you receive your invitation, please inform your manager of the time and date of your appointment.  You might also like to note that UCEA (the Universities &amp; Colleges Employers’ Association, of which QMU is a member) and the five sector HE trade unions have  agreed a <a href=\"https://www.ucea.ac.uk/library/publications/principles-for-working-safely-on-campus-during-the-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic/\">joint statement on vaccinations for staff</a>.</p>\n<p>If you suffer side-effects from having been vaccinated, and are unable to work, you should follow your normal absence reporting procedure, i.e. let your line manager/ designated School/Department contact know as soon as possible.  Your absence should be recorded on iTrent under the following absence reason, ‘COVID Vaccination Recovery’. The first three working days of your absence will be treated as special sick leave; you’ll be paid as normal and your absence will have no effect on your absence record and entitlement to sick pay.</p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/26e0801aed8645e084e981ddd565d36b",
      "title": "Do I need to be vaccinated in order to come to campus?",
      "content": "<p>While the University would strongly encourage you to be vaccinated, it does not require you to be vaccinated to be able to work safely on campus. We don’t need to know if you’ve been vaccinated once, twice or not at all, and if not, why not. We deem your decision to be a private matter. </p>\n<p>If you are concerned about working on  campus  before you have been vaccinated please discuss these concerns with your manager. They will explain the measures in place to protect your health, safety and wellbeing and will discuss what if any adjustments may be needed.</p>"
    }
  ],
